uh for the record tom what's your name full name 
thomas grady barnes iii and where and when were you

00:07.270 --> 00:33.042
born i was born in columbus ohio on august 17 1944. 
okay um when did you first get interested in

00:07.270 --> 00:33.042
astronomy uh really during my freshman week when i 
was at the university of rochester i went there as a

00:33.916 --> 01:01.375
chemistry major and uh and decided that i ought to 
be sure of that so i sat down with the catalog read

00:33.916 --> 01:01.375
all the way through the catalog of majors and said 
astrophysics sounds right i decided i had been

00:33.916 --> 01:01.375
more interested in astrophysics in astronomy 
through my growing up years than chemistry so i

00:33.916 --> 01:01.375
switched majors when did you get your bachelor's 
degree 1966 from Rochester. And then where'd you

01:04.609 --> 01:06.192
go to grad school? University of Toronto. Why? I 
wanted to get, I wanted to do my work with the

01:08.876 --> 01:26.164
Invariable Stars and Don Ferney was, and still is, 
at the University of Toronto and he had done some

01:08.876 --> 01:26.164
really nice work on Cepheids, so I picked Toronto. 
Okay, and when you got there, of course, you took

01:26.431 --> 01:32.280
classes and everything, but what did you do your 
thesis on and under who? I did a master's thesis on

01:33.121 --> 01:47.322
secret galaxy variability with Don Ferny, and 
then I did my Ph.D. thesis also with Ferny on

01:33.121 --> 01:47.322
statistical parallaxes of MIRA variables to get 
the absolute magnitudes. Okay, then you get your

01:47.502 --> 01:51.148
Ph.D., and it's time to get a real job. Where did you 
go? I went to McDonald Observatory as a W.J.

01:57.197 --> 01:59.660
McDonald Fellow in the fall of 1970. How did that 
start? Did you see a notice on the bulletin board or

02:01.582 --> 02:03.985
something like that? In 1970, when I started 
making applications, the job market was really

02:06.128 --> 02:12.176
tight. I mean, it got even tighter later, but it was 
pretty tight. And so I applied for darn near

02:15.320 --> 02:19.725
everything I could find. I honestly don't 
remember where I saw the notice on it. And I don't

02:25.062 --> 02:35.192
remember that I paid much attention to it as an 
application other than I sent it in, as I did a whole

02:25.062 --> 02:35.192
lot of other ones. And then I got a call from Harlan 
Smith offering it to me in the spring of 70. And I had

02:42.239 --> 02:47.844
a couple of other things pending at that time that 
hadn't been resolved. One, for example, at the

02:48.004 --> 02:50.607
University of Western Ontario. that after 
talking with various faculty members, I decided

02:51.734 --> 03:00.405
that I would drop out of the other ones and take the 
MacDonald fellowship. OK, so your first contact

03:02.127 --> 03:04.890
with Harlan was over the telephone. But what was 
your first trip to Texas like? Actually, I met

03:09.356 --> 03:12.640
Harlan before I went to Texas. I met him at the IAU in 
Grenoble in September. August, September,

03:18.413 --> 03:21.717
whenever it was, in 1970. And I remember thinking 
when I met him that this is a character. Because

03:28.605 --> 03:33.211
every word he said about Texas was, it's the best in 
the world. I remember distinctly him telling me

03:33.391 --> 03:42.061
about the accountant at Texas, keeping the books, 
Bill Geist, and how he was the best accountant in

03:33.391 --> 03:42.061
the world. And I thought, this is really 
remarkable that everything there is the best in

03:42.241 --> 03:47.948
the world. Because it wasn't quite the way I'd 
heard it from people before I went there, that

03:48.198 --> 03:56.909
there was some concern about, well, it was kind of a 
new department, a struggling department. But

03:56.929 --> 04:01.355
they had some big telescopes and a lot of access to 
those telescopes, which is why I went. So I moved

04:01.996 --> 04:07.303
there in October 1970.

04:08.228 --> 04:13.155
The department and the observatory were still 
housed in Painter Hall, the old physics building.

04:13.356 --> 04:15.800
Right within close range of the Texas Tower. 
That's right. And in fact, this was not long after

04:16.981 --> 04:20.306
the Texas Tower incident. And that actually 
didn't give me any pause. I didn't consider that as

04:24.052 --> 04:28.579
a negative for going to Texas. It was purely an 
astronomical decision.

04:34.949 --> 04:37.172
When you got there, how? Roughly, how big was the 
department? I mean, how many staff and how many

04:39.422 --> 04:43.347
people at McDonald and the department? It's hard 
for me to remember because it was almost 23 years

04:44.228 --> 04:50.195
ago. But I suppose there were probably six or eight 
faculty, I guess, maybe 10. I don't remember how

04:58.666 --> 05:00.688
many grad students there were. The conditions in 
Painter were very crowded. We were packed into

05:06.683 --> 05:13.129
that particular building, the floors we occupied 
on that building, right up into the attic. So it was

05:14.450 --> 05:20.235
pretty crowded conditions, but it didn't seem to 
bother people, by and large. In fact, it was kind of

05:20.275 --> 05:24.599
nice in some ways because we interacted more 
strongly. Than when you're on three separate

05:24.799 --> 05:26.221
floors. That's right. What did you do when you 
first went there? Well, I went as a postdoc, and so I

05:31.586 --> 05:36.370
got an office with Bill Hubbard and... And Bruce,

05:36.687 --> 05:43.154
God, all of a sudden, I can't remember his last 
name. Josephson Junction Fellow. And I occupied

05:46.537 --> 05:51.142
the desk that Steve Little had before he left. He 
was a previous postdoc. So I started doing the

05:53.584 --> 06:06.137
program that I had planned to do, which was 4N 
hypersensitized plates of globular clusters to

05:53.584 --> 06:06.137
do VRI photometry of mirrors.

06:08.716 --> 06:34.504
okay so you're using ammoniated foreign plates 
that didn't last very long because uh i discovered

06:08.716 --> 06:34.504
pretty quickly even with the 82 inch telescope 
that i wasn't going to be able to get what i wanted

06:08.716 --> 06:34.504
out of the plates and so i looked around for 
something else to do during the the two postdoc

06:08.716 --> 06:34.504
years and i discovered that david lambert was 
working with reinhardt beer of Jet Propulsion Lab

06:34.990 --> 06:43.778
with a Fourier transform spectrometer on the 2.7 
meter, which at that time was still third largest

06:34.990 --> 06:43.778
telescope in the world. And this Fourier 
transform spectrometer was state of the art at

06:44.419 --> 06:47.782
that time. It stayed that way for three or four 
years. And it was fascinating. It was highly

06:52.307 --> 06:54.269
mathematical. They needed somebody with some 
observational experience involved. And so I kind

06:59.934 --> 07:03.057
of fell in with that group. began working FTS stuff 
for six or eight months. And then David offered to

07:07.347 --> 07:11.093
move me on to one of his grants. So I dropped off the 
fellowship. And I stayed with Fourier Transforms

07:15.280 --> 07:22.851
Spectrometry for about six years.

07:23.371 --> 07:38.491
One of the reasons I'm asking you is that you're at a 
place, and you're the assistant director now, I

07:23.371 --> 07:38.491
guess, at McDonald's, that is very heavily 
involved in planetary work, one of the few places

07:23.371 --> 07:38.491
it is, but you're not really a planetary 
astronomer, so you've got a different point of

07:23.371 --> 07:38.491
view. I mean, you know, you're not going to lose 
your grant if you tell the truth, all right? When

07:43.959 --> 07:49.446
you came to UT originally, What would you say was 
the status of planetary astronomy at that time?

07:54.003 --> 07:58.349
Was it an integral part of the department, or was it 
a big deal, or did people just suffer it to be?

08:02.113 --> 08:06.158
I think it was pretty clearly an integral part of 
the department from my perspective. In fact, a lot

08:06.319 --> 08:16.311
of the time I spent observing with that FTS 
instrument was on planets, was on Jupiter,

08:06.319 --> 08:16.311
because that was what Reinhardt Beer was 
interested in doing. We also did long period

08:17.472 --> 08:22.378
variables and some other things which were more of 
interest to me and to David Lambert. But we got

08:22.418 --> 08:34.532
tremendously great amounts of observing time on a 
huge telescope, mostly because, I'm pretty sure,

08:22.418 --> 08:34.532
because of the planetary connection of that 
program. In fact, I think my one planetary

08:36.434 --> 08:45.505
publication is I'm last author of about five or six 
on the first detection of deuterium off the Earth.

08:45.839 --> 08:49.384
which was in deuterated methane in Jupiter from 
that instrument. There was a lot of planetary

08:51.748 --> 08:57.237
astronomy going on on the 107-inch or the 
2.7-meter. I mean, Ed Barker was there doing it.

09:02.385 --> 09:03.727
There were a number of other people involved. Bill 
Hubbard was there with planetary interiors work.

09:08.173 --> 09:11.779
To me, it seemed like it was clearly an integral 
part of the program. One thing that I think is a

09:11.995 --> 09:20.945
mistake in Big and Bright, the history of 
McDonald's, is that no one who was not a faculty

09:11.995 --> 09:20.945
member at UT was ever mentioned. So that leaves out 
Heist-Binrad, it leaves out Tobio, and it leaves

09:20.965 --> 09:24.429
me. And we all, between us, got a substantial 
amount of telescope time. Was there ever any, and

09:29.776 --> 09:36.944
of course, that was because NASA said, you know, 
you've got to use, we give you the money, you've got

09:29.776 --> 09:36.944
to do it. Was there any... jealousy, rage among UT 
faculty members about us outsiders using the

09:41.223 --> 09:49.495
telescope? I don't remember any from then. I 
remember a lot of that later, but I don't remember

09:50.977 --> 09:54.542
any from then. Now that may be because I was so 
intent as a new postdoc and learning this system

09:54.562 --> 10:02.574
and getting established myself that I wasn't 
paying attention to it. I also wasn't connected in

10:03.115 --> 10:10.285
to the faculty and those sorts of discussions to 
the extent that I am today. So I may have just missed

10:10.703 --> 10:19.233
it, but I don't recall there being any anti-solar 
system stuff at that time in the early 70s. Were

10:21.516 --> 10:26.822
planetary astronomers looked down on by real, 
quote, unquote, astronomers? I mean, this is like

10:26.902 --> 10:31.047
a taranto in places like that that didn't have any 
planetary problem. Were you aware of anything

10:31.067 --> 10:32.849
like that? No, I wasn't.

10:37.113 --> 10:43.386
I never got that sense at Toronto or at Rochester, 
although at neither place were there any

10:37.113 --> 10:43.386
planetary astronomers. And so the topic most 
likely didn't come up very much. Do you think

10:47.175 --> 10:49.199
planetary astronomy is real astronomy? Sure. 
Sure, I sure do. I think it's exciting stuff. Now,

10:54.069 --> 10:56.775
as I recall, NASA for many years had this block 
grant for planetary astronomy that they gave to

10:57.025 --> 11:01.851
McDonald. And then in, what, 88 or 87 or something, 
it was switched to individuals or something like

11:01.871 --> 11:07.398
that? That's right. I

11:08.059 --> 11:15.087
became aware of this later on when I got involved in 
administrative matters. But NASA provided a

11:15.187 --> 11:26.982
facilities grant, or a block grant as it was 
called, to McDonald in exchange for access to the

11:15.187 --> 11:26.982
McDonald facilities, principally the 107-inch. 
by planetary astronomers throughout the US. They

11:31.471 --> 11:36.159
had to compete for the telescope time, which in the 
early years meant that Harlan had to agree to give

11:31.471 --> 11:36.159
it to you. Later, there got to be a tack and a real 
competition that was involved. I was the last

11:41.287 --> 11:51.703
person in the world, and I guess because Harlan 
suggested I do it, to write my letters asking for

11:41.287 --> 11:51.703
telescope time in pen and ink on paper. He got a kick 
out of that. But I mean, no kidding. I would really

11:55.667 --> 11:58.389
write them on pen and ink and paper. And I still got 
some Xerox copies of that stuff. And I guess he was

12:01.112 --> 12:02.854
the last observatory. I mean, he was the last 
old-time observatory director that made the

12:02.894 --> 12:10.041
decisions without an observing committee or 
anything like that. Is that true? That's right.

12:12.003 --> 12:13.024
During most of the 70s. Now, I'm not sure what year 
it changed, but it was right around 1978. It may

12:17.649 --> 12:21.893
have been a year or two earlier or a year or two, 
certainly not more than a year or so later. that

12:22.767 --> 12:51.660
prior to that time harlan kept a huge poster board 
of uh of graph paper basically on in his office and

12:22.767 --> 12:51.660
he had each telescope and he had uh the calendar on 
the x-axis and each telescope was listed on the

12:22.767 --> 12:51.660
y-axis and he would write in in pencil the 
observing programs and since and he wrote him in on

12:22.767 --> 12:51.660
pencil because he would change them right up to the 
day of the run there were times when uh when my

12:52.079 --> 13:00.728
observing runs were changed at the last minute for 
a variety of reasons, none of which seemed to me

12:52.079 --> 13:00.728
good at the time, but I'm sure they were good in his 
eyes. That went on until, as I say, the late 70s when

13:01.949 --> 13:20.128
the scheduling was turned over to David Evans, and 
then maybe pretty quickly Rob Robinson began

13:01.949 --> 13:20.128
helping him with it, and they did it in a similar way 
in the sense that they had golf tees and pegboard,

13:20.783 --> 13:29.678
and they reproduced Harlan's graph paper system 
in a different mechanism. But it was still the same

13:29.698 --> 13:30.759
thing. You submitted your proposals. They sort of 
read them and decided who got telescope time and

13:31.921 --> 13:36.629
put the pegboard up accordingly. And then it was in 
the early to mid-'80s, we went over to an actual

13:37.210 --> 13:44.682
tack. Telescope Allocation Committee, which 
reviewed the proposals, made decisions, and

13:45.438 --> 13:55.818
those decisions were honored by Harlan and now by 
the current director, Frank Bash. Honest Engine

13:56.639 --> 14:07.159
Scouts Honor is committee allocation of 
telescope time better than beneficent despot.

14:07.392 --> 14:10.957
I've thought a lot about that because I've seen 
both of them at Texas. And my conclusion is that

14:11.157 --> 14:17.806
from the point of view of the science that gets 
done, I don't think it makes a whit worth of

14:11.157 --> 14:17.806
difference. From the point of view of the feelings 
of the people proposing for time and getting the

14:18.326 --> 14:26.277
time, it makes a tremendous difference. Because 
when there's a group of colleagues who evaluate

14:26.297 --> 14:33.366
one's proposal, come to their best decision, and 
then render that judgment, there is more

14:33.633 --> 14:43.728
acceptance than when a single individual says 
I've made the decision based on my best reading of

14:33.633 --> 14:43.728
the circumstances. So I don't think it makes any 
difference in the science that gets done. I don't

14:46.832 --> 14:53.261
think it made any difference when it went from 
Harlan to David Evans to the TAC in who got

14:46.832 --> 14:53.261
telescope time. I haven't done the statistics to 
prove it, but I don't believe there was any

14:53.362 --> 14:56.306
difference. But there was a tremendous 
improvement in the acceptance of the telescope

14:57.147 --> 15:03.336
schedule by the people listed on it. Now, 
currently, you're the assistant director at

15:03.923 --> 15:09.308
McDonald's, and Frank is on vacation. So I'll hit 
you, because usually it's like the co-pilot

15:11.290 --> 15:16.074
always lands the plane. The assistant director 
does all the work. What's the status of planetary

15:19.437 --> 15:23.261
astronomy at UT and Texas today? I think it's as 
healthy as it was at any time in the history of

15:24.422 --> 15:33.390
Texas. There's obviously the difference that 
there is not someone with an intense interest in

15:33.944 --> 15:42.673
planetary astronomy in the directorship 
position. That changed when Harlan retired as

15:42.894 --> 15:46.798
director and Frank came in. Frank's a radio 
astronomer interested in galaxies, in galactic

15:47.198 --> 15:51.303
structure. And he's not hostile to planetary 
astronomy, but it's not of intense interest to him

15:51.823 --> 15:57.229
such as it was for Harlan. So that changed. The 
quality of the research hasn't changed at all.

16:03.329 --> 16:05.252
We've got both the Cochrans are still there. Larry 
Trafton's there. Ed Barker's there. There are a

16:08.797 --> 16:13.424
couple of postdocs that have come and gone working 
in that area. Artie Hotzis is there now working

16:13.705 --> 16:16.248
with Bill Cochran. The emphasis of the program has 
changed somewhat as the years go by, but that's

16:17.009 --> 16:22.838
normal in any research program. So I think the 
quality of the program now is as good as it's ever

16:23.359 --> 16:28.707
been. The amount of telescope time granted to 
planetary astronomy in this competitive TAC

16:29.294 --> 16:35.900
environment has stayed high. It consistently 
exceeds the amount of time that's been funded by

16:36.921 --> 16:43.507
NASA. We still get quite a few outside observers 
coming in. There's Drew Potter from JSC. There's

16:51.015 --> 16:58.862
Alan Stern from Southwest Research Institute and 
others who come in to do make use of the McDonald

16:59.467 --> 17:00.869
facilities. So I think it's as healthy as it's ever 
been. Here's something that goes for astronomy in

17:04.514 --> 17:08.559
general as well as planetary astronomy. Times are 
getting tough, folks. What do you see in the

17:11.423 --> 17:12.504
future? And I think planetary astronomy will 
just, because we both agree it's part of

17:12.544 --> 17:21.295
astronomy, so it's going to rise and fall with the 
tide. What do you think's in the future for the next

17:22.917 --> 17:26.402
couple of years, the next couple of decades? With 
respect to planetary astronomy at McDonald?

17:30.210 --> 17:35.037
Astronomy in general and planetary astronomy at 
McDonald. I think for McDonald, things are really

17:35.057 --> 17:37.080
looking up. McDonald over all fields. Because on 
April 1st, the Regents approved the

17:39.984 --> 17:55.046
spectroscopic survey telescope, which is the 
primary will have a hexagonal shape, 91 hexagonal

17:39.984 --> 17:55.046
segments put together to make a hex primary, which 
will be 10 meters by 11 meters. So it'll be a huge

17:55.547 --> 17:57.570
telescope to go at McDonald. Assuming that we can 
get all our partners to sign the legal agreements

17:58.090 --> 18:07.661
and that the bids for construction come back 
within budget, we will have that in full operation

17:58.090 --> 18:07.661
by sometime in 1997. And you're going to put it on 
flat top? It'll be on flat top. Which is now called

18:10.764 --> 18:11.926
Mount? Mount Fulks. Right. But it's flat top to us 
old-timers, right? Right. So I see the prospects

18:17.692 --> 18:22.377
from McDonald being outstanding. And the 
spectroscopic survey telescope, and we

18:22.397 --> 18:26.562
dedicated the spectroscopy for... minute field 
of view, so it's not appropriate for large-scale

18:26.896 --> 18:33.749
imaging, small imaging, okay. I see planetary 
astronomy having a very, very big role to play in

18:35.011 --> 18:41.484
that. One question that I have on my list here is how 
well do you think astronomers in general and

18:41.604 --> 18:49.579
planetary astronomers in particular have sold 
their field And it's particularly appropriate to

18:50.268 --> 19:02.762
ask you, because I think McDonald has done a 
tremendous job compared to, say, Mount Wilson and

18:50.268 --> 19:02.762
Palomar, who generally have a the public be damned 
attitude, I think it's fair to say. I mean, you're

19:03.643 --> 19:09.610
obviously doing a lot with the general public. And 
as you know, Susan Shorn is the assistant editor

19:09.630 --> 19:15.136
for Stardate. That was Harlan's idea to do it. And 
do you think that has worked out well to really get

19:19.428 --> 19:24.697
the public involved? Oh, yeah. I mean, it makes a 
tremendous difference in how we are treated

19:25.198 --> 19:33.732
within the state of Texas by the legislature and 
the university. Frank has said to me that he has sat

19:35.695 --> 19:45.672
in meetings with prominent members of the 
legislature, or lunches with prominent members

19:35.695 --> 19:45.672
of the legislature, who, and friends of the 
observatory who are discussing the role of

19:46.242 --> 20:07.261
McDonald with these people, who have said that 
their connection to McDonald is through

19:46.242 --> 20:07.261
Stardate, through the magazine, through the 
radio program, that they take great pride in

19:46.242 --> 20:07.261
driving through Washington DC and hearing on the 
radio Stardate come on and reference the

19:46.242 --> 20:07.261
University of Texas at Austin. So our public 
outreach program is very effective for us in

20:07.281 --> 20:15.709
maintaining a presence with the political 
structure in the state of Texas. But that is a

20:18.295 --> 20:20.898
reason for doing it. It's not the primary reason 
for doing it in my mind, nor was it in Harlan's, nor

20:20.998 --> 20:25.483
is it in Frank's. That's a spinoff from you do it 
because the people who have paid the bill for all of

20:26.124 --> 20:39.638
our research have a right to hear the results from 
that research in a way they can understand. And you

20:41.069 --> 20:49.483
have a huge number of other things going on with the 
public, you know, little observing sessions down

20:41.069 --> 20:49.483
at the visitor center and the visitor center. Have 
you ever thought about painting the shutters

20:50.465 --> 20:56.335
yellow and putting up a McDonald's on the 
mountain? Because everyone always expects...

20:57.978 --> 20:59.040
McDonald's Golden Arches. I know that the public 
oftentimes get confused between McDonald's, the

20:59.260 --> 21:10.196
restaurant chain, and McDonald's Observatory, 
but no, we haven't actually thought about putting

20:59.260 --> 21:10.196
Yellow Arches out there. Maybe if the funding 
situation gets bad enough, we can approach them.

21:13.040 --> 21:14.802
Have you ever approached McDonald's? No, not to my 
knowledge. Because, I mean, I don't know how many

21:16.625 --> 21:21.572
times I've been on the mountain, people say, you 
know, where do we get the hamburgers? And the

21:21.552 --> 21:24.797
second question is, where's the gasoline 
station? Right. And where's the restroom?

21:30.686 --> 21:44.687
But that is in marked contrast to a number of other 
observatories that we could name, that probably

21:30.686 --> 21:44.687
because they had private funding sources, and I'm 
talking about Molson and Belmar, had only

21:30.686 --> 21:44.687
discussed for the general public. There's two 
things that underlie that, I think. One of them is

21:50.476 --> 21:53.339
that in the will from W.J. McDonald, in which he 
gave the bequest to the university to erect and

21:53.359 --> 22:12.381
equip, if I can remember the quote, it's something 
like, to erect and equip an observatory for the

21:53.359 --> 22:12.381
study and the promotion of the study of the science 
of astronomy. And that promotion of the study of

22:12.941 --> 22:17.867
the science of astronomy in his will has been used 
as the justification for a strong public outreach

22:18.218 --> 22:24.667
program. But I think that reason is more of a 
post-hope justification rather than something

22:25.188 --> 22:33.920
that started it. It really started and was 
maintained and grew because Harlan Smith

22:34.241 --> 22:38.887
believed in it. He was absolutely dedicated to a 
strong public outreach program. One of the key

22:44.515 --> 22:47.179
things he wanted to accomplish and he did 
accomplish. personal opinion why do you think

22:47.530 --> 23:13.470
that kind of attitude is so rare among astronomers 
especially since now basically we're all

22:47.530 --> 23:13.470
supported by public money in one way or another um 
you know i think at the root the root reason for it in

22:47.530 --> 23:13.470
my mind is that is that most researchers are not 
very facile in dealing with other people They're

23:14.345 --> 23:29.704
outstanding in dealing with the technicalities 
of a science, in dealing with the mathematics,

23:14.345 --> 23:29.704
with the instrumentation, with the observing 
programs, with the observing plans, with the

23:14.345 --> 23:29.704
getting of the money, the writing of the grants, 
the writing of the papers. But in everyday normal

23:30.365 --> 23:39.036
social environments, I think an awful lot of 
high-tech researchers, like astronomers, are

